<DOC><DOCNO> AP880525-0199 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 1627EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u w BC-HouseDisclosures-Georgia     05-25 0753</FIRST><SECOND>BC-House Disclosures-Georgia,750</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here are capsule summaries of the financialdisclosure forms filed by members of the House from Georgia for1987 and released Wednesday.   Income includes the House salary, honoraria earnings fromwriting and speeches and other income such as dividends andinterest.   Earnings by the representatives' spouses and dependents are notincluded in the income figure.   The asset and liability figures for the representatives do notinclude holdings and liabilities of spouses and dependents.   Representatives are permitted to keep honoraria earnings fromspeeches and writings up to 30 percent of their salary. For nearlyall members, their salary was $89,500 at the end of 1987. Thespeaker of the House was paid at the annualized rate of $115,000and the Democratic and Republican leaders were paid at theannualized rate of $99,500.   Many members receive honoraria above the limit and donate theexcess to charity.   In their financial disclosure forms, representatives are allowedto list income, assets and liabilities by ranges instead ofspecific figures. However, some representatives provide specificfigures.   In their listing of assets, representatives do not have toinclude their personal residences and vehicles. Gifts, thoughlisted, are not counted in income figure given here.</TEXT><TEXT>   LINDSAY THOMAS   Income: $103,238.   Honoraria: $13,800.   Gifts: None.   Assets: $254,330.   Liabilities: $62,702.   He reported exact amounts of his income, assets and liabilities.His total assets nearly doubled in value during the year when heinherited a house and 15 acres in Screven, Ga., valued at $125,000.</TEXT><TEXT>   CHARLES HATCHER   Income: $103,983-$104,983.   Honoraria: $16,500.   Gifts: None.   Assets: $5,001-$15,000.   Liabilities: $20,002-$65,000.   His travel and lodging expenses on five trips were paid bybusiness organizations that invited him to speak.</TEXT><TEXT>   RICHARD RAY   Income: $137,239-$189,233.   Honoraria: $26,250, of which $370 donated to charity.   Gifts: $750.   Assets: $800,012-$1,340,000 and up.   Liabilities: $375-014-$1,000,000.   Ray received one gift, a Steuben American Eagle, which he saidcame from 10 individuals who contributed $75 each toward itspurchase. Ray, a member of the House Armed Services Committee,collected $20,750 in honoraria from defense contractors andaccepted expense reimbursements from defense contractors for ninetrips in connection with speeches or tours of their facilities.</TEXT><TEXT>   PATRICK SWINDALL   Income: $263,290.   Honoraria: $7,300.   Gifts: None.   Assets: $2,265,660.   Liabilities: $334,000.   He gave exact amounts of his income, assets and liabilities. Hisassets include three buildings and eight acres of land in EastPoint, Ga., valued a $1 million, and a promissory note for $1million he received in connection with the 1986 sale of real estatein downtown Atlanta. The Anti-Defamation League of Atlanta paidtravel and lodging expenses for Swindall and his wife during a10-day trip to Israel last year.</TEXT><TEXT>   JOHN LEWIS   Income: $103,059-$113,058.   Honoraria: $10,575.   Gifts: None.   Assets: None.   Liabilities: None.   Lewis accepted expense reimbursements from sponsoringorganizations on four trips for speaking engagements.</TEXT><TEXT>   NEWT GINGRICH   Income: $122,284-$133,283.   Honoraria: $29,800, of which $3,915 donated to charity.   Gifts: None.   Assets: $20,002-$65,000.   Liabilities: $25,003-$80,000.   Gingrich, a leader of the Republican right in the House, made 24trips during the year where his expenses were paid by local orstate GOP organizations or by political action committees ofconservative groups.</TEXT><TEXT>   BUDDY DARDEN   Income: $114,233.   Honoraria: $26,750, of which $1,000 donated to charity.   Gifts: None.   Assets: $15,001-$60,000.   Liabilities: None.   Darden, a member of the House Armed Services Committee, accepted$19,000 in honoraria from defense contractors. He also acceptedtravel and lodging reimbursements from 10 defense contractors fortrips made in connection with speeches or tours at their facilities.</TEXT><TEXT>   ROY ROWLAND   Income: $158,513-$164,012.   Honoraria: $10,000.   Gifts: None.   Assets: $360,009-$870,000.   Liabilities: None.   Rowland, a physician, accepted $7,000 in honoraria from theAmerican Medical Association and its political action committee. Healso accepted expense reimbursements from the AMA for twoconferences in Florida.</TEXT><TEXT>   ED JENKINS   Income: $153,738-$247,233.   Honoraria: $25,250.   Gifts: None.   Assets: $320,009-840,000.   Liabilities: None.   Jenkins sold his interest in two pieces of real estate inPickens County, Ga., during 1987, receiving capital gains ofbetween $15,000 and $50,000 on each sale. He listed two assetsowned by his wife _ a store building and one-half interest in a100-acre farm _ that were valued at between $50,000 and $100,000each.</TEXT><TEXT>   DOUG BARNARD   Income: $142,339-$148,838.   Honoraria: $52,355, of which $26,800 donated to charity.   Gifts: None.   Assets: $15,001-$50,000.   Liabilities: None.   Barnard, a senior member of the House Banking Committee, gotmost of his honoraria from financial groups. His travel and lodgingexpenses on 22 trips last year were paid by organizationssponsoring his appearance at their meetings or seminars.</TEXT></DOC>